label chapter6:

    # [Scene: Verdant Spire Rooftop Farm | Golden Hour]

    scene bg ch6_601bcb_1 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Triumphant, driving strings with percussive hand-drums — very high energy]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Cheer rising from below; the soft slap of modular floats against pilings; the hum of irrigation]
    "You breathe in—full, sharp, like pulling tidewater into a lung. The air tastes of wet soil and salt and citrus from the promenade below. Every leaf on the rooftop seems to hum. You can feel the city’s heart beating against your ribs: fast, hopeful, impossibly alive."
    "A radio on a weatherproof crate crackles. Someone calls up the line: “Mayor Chen’s on the promenade—she’s announcing the funding now.” The words land like lightning. Your stomach does a small, traitorous flip that you welcome."
    "You remember the market’s hush before you stepped to the mic last night, the elderly woman’s hand on your pendant, the metallic taste of the choice. Now that hush is unspooled into sound—applause, whistles, the clack"
    "of tools put down and raised like flags. The arousal that has kept you taut for days snaps into an exultant cord."

    scene bg ch6_601bcb_2 at full_bg
    show emil_kwon at left:
        zoom 0.7

    emil_kwon "They did it. You did it."
    "You turn. He’s smiling—unforced, quiet—but there is a brightness in his sea-glass eyes that makes your chest loosen. He smells faintly of brine and wood-smoke. You can see a smear of dark soil on his thumbnail; it anchors the moment in the tactile world you both love."
    show maya_reyes at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_reyes "We did it. Everyone did."

    emil_kwon "And look—"
    "He nods toward the water. '—there are the first prototype modules. Floating like stubborn little islands.' (He laughs; it’s a short, delighted sound.) 'They actually float.'"
    "You watch the line of modular breakwaters drift by, each one a patchwork of reclaimed plastic, knotted rope, and planted reeds. They bob sturdily, designed to eat wave energy and grow habitat. For a second, the city looks like a living mosaic of inventions and people's hands."
    hide emil_kwon
    hide maya_reyes

    scene bg ch6_601bcb_3 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Mayor's voice amplified, steady and warm; the crowd below responds in waves of applause]
    show mayor_lila_chen at left:
        zoom 0.7

    mayor_lila_chen "Today the council voted to fund our hybrid resilience plan—engineering where it must be, living shorelines where we can—anchored by legally binding community co-op governance. Targeted funds for retrofits will be released this quarter."
    "The announcement is a rope of sound that pulls the crowd forward. You feel it in your teeth and bones. Your name is not needed; your work is. Diego’s grin splits his face like a map."
    show diego_ramos at right:
        zoom 0.7

    diego_ramos "We’re forming the co-op now! I’ve got bylaws half-typed and half-drawn on the back of a tarp—bring string and pens!"
    "Diego’s voice is a rush of energy—practical and raucous. He bounds toward a group below already forming a circle to plan. People pass up cups of sweet tea and fried dough like benediction. Hands clasp. Asha"
    "stands near the feed, her silver hair catching the light. She watches you with those warm, amber spectacles and a smile that says: you learned how to hold what matters."
    show asha_karim at center:
        zoom 0.7

    asha_karim "You kept them in the picture,' she says, not loudly—only to you. 'That takes courage and stubbornness in equal measure."
    "You answer with a laugh that trembles on the edge of a sob. It’s relief and exhaustion braided together."

    menu:
        "Help Diego set up the co-op table":
            "You move down the ladder with Diego, carrying a crate of seedlings and a stack of raw-paper bylaws. The market swells around you; hands help you unfold the table, fingers sticky with sugar and ink. You talk through membership tiers and workshop schedules between bites of fried dough."
        "Stay with Emil to watch the prototypes pass":
            "You stay on the rooftop. Emil spreads his satchel open and pulls out a cloth-wrapped bundle—tools, a thermos, and a seedling. You watch the breakwaters pass like a small convoy, and the quiet between you is loud with meaning."

    # --- merge ---
    "You choose to stay—only briefly—because the rooftop’s vantage feels like a promise you need to witness before you descend. Emil steps closer, a little too close in the way that makes your breath hitch."
    hide mayor_lila_chen
    show emil_kwon at left:
        zoom 0.7

    emil_kwon "I brought you something."
    "He unwraps the cloth slowly, as if ceremony were owed. 'Not data. Not a model. Just a seedling. Salt-tolerant cordgrass—sourced from Diego’s marsh, grown on the spare terrace. Soil still clinging to it.'"
    "He sets the tiny plant into your palm. The earth is cool and grainy; the roots seem to tremble at the contact. You press your thumb to the stem and feel an electric, ridiculous certainty: this small thing will outlast any speech."
    hide diego_ramos
    show maya_reyes at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_reyes "It’s perfect."

    emil_kwon "So are you."
    "He flushes, then backtracks, half-smiles. 'I mean—your plan. You. The way you keep asking the hard questions.'"
    "You laugh, and the sound breaks free like a wave. You want to ask him to stay; you want to tell him that the co-op clause will be more than ink now—that it will be a living contract written in seedlings and late-night trainings and shared meals. The words hover."

    menu:
        "Promise to plant a patch together tomorrow":
            "You fold your hand over his and say the easiest, truest thing: 'Tomorrow, first light.' He grins like a sunrise. Plans form—who will bring soil, who will ferry the floats, whether to tether nets for seedlings. The future feels movable, like a map you can redraw."
        "Pull him into a quiet embrace instead":
            "You step in, closing the distance. His hands find your waist, and for a moment the world narrows to the press of fabric and the warming of skin. The city roars on below—a distant orchestra. When you pull back, both of you are smiling in a way that promises work and rest in the same breath."

    # --- merge ---
    "You choose both without rigidly choosing either: a promise and an embrace braided into one. The crowd’s cheer below swells into a collective exhale. Celebration is not just noise; it is the sound of plans being given oxygen."
    # [Scene: Tideward Promenade | Dusk]
    hide asha_karim
    hide emil_kwon
    hide maya_reyes

    scene bg ch6_601bcb_4 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Upbeat folk rhythm layered with brass accents; laughter and clapping punctuate the beat]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Frying pans, chatter, the slap of water against pilings; someone plays a hand drum in the background]
    "You make your way down into the market. The smell of citrus oil and frying dough wraps around you like a shawl. People move in purposeful loops—repairs coordinated like choreography. Children run between pedal-powered pumps, trailing salt-spray and hope."
    "Noah Ortega is there, less polished than the conference room but present in a way that makes your throat tighten. He approaches you with a paper cup—coffee steaming into the cooling air. Up close, the steel-gray"
    "of his eyes softens; the high collar of his coat does little to hide the wear of the day."
    show noah_ortega at left:
        zoom 0.7

    noah_ortega "You kept them in the picture,' he says, mirroring Asha’s words but with an authority shaped by numbers and deadlines. 'I pushed the Consortium for a different line item. They were skeptical—until Diego laid out the community-maintenance model. Your clause gave them a frame. They’ll fund pilot materials and a knowledge-transfer fund. Don’t mistake this for surrender; it’s leverage. Use it."
    "He offers you his hand, not quite a handshake—more a transfer of responsibility. You notice the signet ring on his finger, the slow way his jaw unclenches."
    show maya_reyes at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_reyes "I’ll hold you to that, Noah. Oversight isn't the same as ownership."

    noah_ortega "I know. And I’ll be the first to answer when oversight needs teeth."
    "His concession is not theatrical. It’s measured, uneasy, and real. You accept the cup more for the ritual than the coffee, and it grounds you. Community control backed by Consortium resources—it’s messy, necessary compromise. The city is refusing simple answers and inventing messy ones instead."
    show diego_ramos at center:
        zoom 0.7

    diego_ramos "We’re rostering build crews. You should see the list—grandmothers who mend nets, kids who can bolt anything, and old welders who think my design is sacrilege but come anyway. We’ve got momentum."
    "You feel the momentum like a physical thing: a swell that lifts your feet. Hands press plants into your arms, strangers slap your back, someone tacks a handmade badge to your jacket that reads: 'Kept in the Picture.' It is ridiculous and holy."
    "Asha Karim sidles next to you, offering a thermos of something herbal and hot. She studies the crowd and then you. There is no lecture in her face, only affirmation."
    hide noah_ortega
    show asha_karim at left:
        zoom 0.7

    asha_karim "You were practical. You were stubborn. And you let yourself ask for help. That will be the thing they tell their grandkids about."
    "You picture such stories—small mythologies of people who planted where tides tried to erase them. The thought makes your eyes sting, not from salt but from something like gratitude."
    hide maya_reyes
    hide diego_ramos
    hide asha_karim

    scene bg ch6_601bcb_5 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: A swelling, warm chorus; the strings return with a triumphant lead]
    "Emil Kwon finds your hand again, fingers warm and callused. He presses the soil-smeared thumb to the tiny seedling’s stem, as if making a vow."
    show emil_kwon at left:
        zoom 0.7

    emil_kwon "Promise me something else?"
    "He searches your face, honest. 'That when it’s hard—when funding slows or the weather takes a bite—you’ll come back to this: the smell of frying dough, Diego’s ridiculous bylaws, the way people show up.'"
    show maya_reyes at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_reyes "I promise."
    "You mean it with the slow gravity of someone who has lived through loss and decided to keep building anyway."
    "He leans forward, then back, then forward again—the small shuffles lovers make when they want the moment to stretch. His sea-glass eyes are luminous in the string-light glow."

    emil_kwon "Then promise me I can keep doing this with you. Not just the work—but when the city is quiet, you and me, planting a ridiculous patch of cordgrass in a ridiculous place."
    "You don’t have to think. The choice has already been made by the way you’ve been living: in shared shifts, joint meals, hands gritty with salt and soil and ink."

    maya_reyes "Yes. With you."
    "He laughs, a sound like sails catching wind. Around you, the promenade breaks into applause—not at a speech but at a shared, human arrangement being sealed: a pact of labor and care, of love and governance, of policy signed and rooted in living things."
    hide emil_kwon
    hide maya_reyes

    scene bg ch6_601bcb_6 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Climactic orchestration, choir underlay; percussion pounding a steady, hopeful rhythm]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Roar of the crowd, horns, laughter, a single, sustained cheer that feels like a tide turning]
    "You stand there—chest open, hands dirty, hair damp from the day’s salt—and you feel the shape of the future for the first time as something you can reach for, not just hold in theory. The Council’s"
    "vote, the co-op clause, Noah’s resources, Diego’s organizing, Asha’s steady counsel, Emil’s steady hands—they are threads of the same rope pulling the city forward."
    "A child runs past and presses a reed into your hand like an offering before sprinting off. You tuck it into the soil of the seedling Emil gave you. The plant bends to the touch, alive and unafraid."
    "You close your eyes for a breath and in that breath you name the city as you hope it will become: noisy, imperfect, stubbornly human."

    scene bg ch6_601bcb_7 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Gentle, resolving cadence; the triumphant theme softens into a warm, sustained chord]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Distant breakers, a soft wind over reeds, the crowd’s murmur settling into contented chatter]
    "You let the moment sit a second longer—full and loud and utterly real. Tonight is celebration. Tomorrow will be work, and the day after that, more work. But tonight you and Emil and the city share a victory fragile as a seed and sturdy as a breakwater."
    show maya_reyes at left:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_reyes "We kept them in the picture. We promised them a seat at the table—and we planted the table into the ground."
    "You squeeze Emil’s hand. He squeezes back. The sound of the market becomes a single, steady heartbeat. You lean into him. The night presses in, warm and damp and alive."
    hide maya_reyes

    scene bg ch6_601bcb_8 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Final, uplifting chord resolves]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: A last, contented cheer rises and fades]

    scene bg ch6_601bcb_9 at full_bg
    "THE END"
